<body>
<div class="cal-wrap">
 
  <div class="cal-header">
    <div class="cal-eyebrow">The Language Firm — Federal Integrity Track</div>
    <h1 class="cal-title">Federal Findings<br><em>Digest</em></h1>
    <p class="cal-meta">February 2026 &nbsp;·&nbsp; <strong>9 findings</strong> &nbsp;·&nbsp; Published March 16, 2026</p>
    <p class="cal-desc">Federal programs &amp; fiscal compliance intelligence for K-12 federal program directors, fiscal agents, and district administrators.</p>
  </div>
 
  <div class="cal-context">
    <strong>How this digest works.</strong> Each entry summarizes a federal finding, enforcement action, resolution agreement, guidance document, or regulatory activity published in February 2026. Every entry includes a factual summary of the source document, a TLF interpretation of the compliance implication, and a Your Action section translating that implication into concrete steps your team can take. Source links are provided for independent verification.
  </div>
 
  <div class="cal-filters">
    <div class="f-pill active" data-filter="all" onclick="filterProgram('all')">All programs</div>
    <div class="f-pill" data-filter="title1" onclick="filterProgram('title1')">Title I</div>
    <div class="f-pill" data-filter="idea" onclick="filterProgram('idea')">IDEA</div>
    <div class="f-pill" data-filter="ocr" onclick="filterProgram('ocr')">OCR</div>
    <div class="f-pill" data-filter="perkins" onclick="filterProgram('perkins')">Perkins</div>
    <div class="f-pill" data-filter="noaction" onclick="filterProgram('noaction')">No K-12 action</div>
  </div>
 
  <div class="cal-entries" id="entries">
 
    <!-- TITLE I -->
    <div class="cal-section-label" data-section="title1">Title I</div>
 
    <div class="cal-entry title1" data-program="title1">
      <div class="entry-inner">
        <div class="entry-top">
          <div class="entry-badge">Title I</div>
          <div class="entry-type-badge">Guidance / Press Release</div>
          <div class="entry-title-block">
            <div class="entry-title">ED Issues Guidance on Strategic Staffing Models and Title II Flexibility for Teacher Workforce Innovation</div>
            <div class="entry-date">Office of Elementary and Secondary Education · February 9, 2026</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="entry-sublabel">What it says</div>
        <p class="entry-body">ED sent guidance to states and districts emphasizing existing flexibilities under ESEA to use Title II, Part A funds to implement innovative teacher workforce strategies, including strategic staffing models designed to improve academic achievement. Districts can use Title II funds for non-traditional staffing designs that strengthen educator support and expand instructional options.</p>
        <div class="entry-sublabel">TLF Interpretation</div>
        <div class="entry-tlf-note">This guidance clarifies that districts may use Title II, Part A funds to implement innovative and strategic staffing models, including non-traditional educator roles and differentiated staffing structures. The guidance expands recognized allowable uses of Title II-A beyond traditional professional development. Districts should review their Title II-A budgets and applications to determine whether strategic staffing initiatives are allowable and aligned with their comprehensive needs assessment. Any workforce innovation funded with Title II-A must be documented as supporting educator effectiveness and included in the district's Title II-A application and expenditure justifications.</div>
        <div class="entry-action">
          <div class="entry-action-label">Your Action</div>
          <ul>
            <li>Review your Title II, Part A budget and district application to identify whether current or planned staffing innovations are documented as allowable under this guidance.</li>
            <li>If your school uses teacher leadership roles, instructional coaching models, or team-based teaching structures, confirm these are referenced in your comprehensive needs assessment and Title II-A expenditure justifications.</li>
            <li>Brief your HR and curriculum leads on this clarification so any workforce redesign proposals are routed through federal programs review before budget commitments are made.</li>
            <li>Verify supplement-not-supplant documentation is in place for any Title II-A staffing expenditure before the next expenditure cycle.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="entry-source"><strong>Source:</strong> <a href="https://www.ed.gov/about/news/press-release/us-department-of-education-highlights-flexibility-federal-education-funding-support-innovative-teacher-workforce-strategies-states-0" target="_blank">U.S. Department of Education press release, February 9, 2026 ↗</a> · ESEA Title II, Part A · 34 CFR §200.25</div>
      </div>
    </div>
 
    <div class="cal-entry title1" data-program="title1">
      <div class="entry-inner">
        <div class="entry-top">
          <div class="entry-badge">Title I</div>
          <div class="entry-type-badge">Federal Register Notice</div>
          <div class="entry-title-block">
            <div class="entry-title">Title I State, LEA, and School Data Collection and Reporting Requirements — Comment Period Open</div>
            <div class="entry-date">Office of Elementary and Secondary Education · February 24, 2026</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="entry-sublabel">What it says</div>
        <p class="entry-body">ED published a Federal Register notice seeking public comment (due April 27, 2026) on an extension without changes of Title I, Part A data collection and reporting requirements for SEAs, LEAs, and schools under ESEA. This is a routine Paperwork Reduction Act extension, but comments are being solicited on the burden and necessity of current Title I reporting requirements.</p>
        <div class="entry-sublabel">TLF Interpretation</div>
        <div class="entry-tlf-note">This is a routine PRA extension notice — no regulatory changes are proposed. However, the comment period is an opportunity for districts experiencing significant administrative burden with current Title I reporting to document that burden formally. Comments submitted during this window become part of the administrative record and can influence future modifications to reporting requirements. This notice does not change current obligations.</div>
        <div class="entry-action">
          <div class="entry-action-label">Your Action</div>
          <ul>
            <li>No immediate compliance action required. Current Title I reporting requirements remain unchanged.</li>
            <li>If your school or district experiences significant burden with current Title I data collection — volume, frequency, or systems complexity — consider submitting a comment by April 27, 2026. Comments on burden are appropriate and useful input for federal agencies.</li>
            <li>File this entry as documentation that your program reviewed the notice and confirmed no regulatory changes affect current obligations.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="entry-source"><strong>Source:</strong> Federal Register notice, February 24, 2026 · Title I, Part A data collection requirements · Comment period closes April 27, 2026</div>
      </div>
    </div>
 
    <!-- IDEA -->
    <div class="cal-section-label" data-section="idea">IDEA</div>
 
    <div class="cal-entry idea" data-program="idea">
      <div class="entry-inner">
        <div class="entry-top">
          <div class="entry-badge">IDEA</div>
          <div class="entry-type-badge">Audit Report</div>
          <div class="entry-title-block">
            <div class="entry-title">National Assessment of IDEA Overview — Implementation Study Executive Summary</div>
            <div class="entry-date">Institute of Education Sciences / National Center for Education Evaluation · February 26, 2026</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="entry-sublabel">What it says</div>
        <p class="entry-body">A congressionally mandated study providing a national picture of state agency implementation of early intervention programs for infants and toddlers (IDEA Part C) and state and school district implementation of special education programs (IDEA Part B). The study examines Response to Intervention implementation, Coordinated Early Intervening Services, and state support for transitions.</p>
        <div class="entry-sublabel">TLF Interpretation</div>
        <div class="entry-tlf-note">This study provides national benchmarks on how states and districts implement IDEA Part B and Part C, with specific focus on RTI, CEIS, and transition supports. While it does not create new regulatory requirements, it offers a research-based benchmark against which state monitoring agencies may evaluate local implementation. State agencies will have access to the same data — meaning local practices that diverge from national benchmarks may attract scrutiny in the next monitoring cycle.</div>
        <div class="entry-action">
          <div class="entry-action-label">Your Action</div>
          <ul>
            <li>Obtain and review the IES executive summary. Flag any implementation practices highlighted nationally that differ from your current local approach.</li>
            <li>Cross-reference your CEIS expenditure records against the 15% cap and confirm documentation of how funds were used for early intervening services.</li>
            <li>Review your child find procedures and evaluation timelines against the benchmarks referenced in the study. Confirm timelines are being met and documented.</li>
            <li>Brief your special education director and RTI coordinator on the national findings before your next state monitoring cycle.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="entry-source"><strong>Source:</strong> Institute of Education Sciences / NCEE, February 26, 2026 · IDEA Part B (20 U.S.C. §1400 et seq.) · 34 CFR §300.226 (CEIS)</div>
      </div>
    </div>
 
    <!-- OCR -->
    <div class="cal-section-label" data-section="ocr">OCR</div>
 
    <div class="cal-entry ocr" data-program="ocr">
      <div class="entry-inner">
        <div class="entry-top">
          <div class="entry-badge">OCR</div>
          <div class="entry-type-badge">Resolution Agreement</div>
          <div class="entry-title-block">
            <div class="entry-title">OCR Resolution: Section 504 / Title II Compliance — Student with Disability Denied Services and Evaluations</div>
            <div class="entry-date">Office for Civil Rights · February 2026</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="entry-sublabel">What it says</div>
        <p class="entry-body">OCR resolved a complaint finding that a district failed to provide a student with a disability timely evaluations, appropriate services, and required procedural safeguards under Section 504 and Title II of the ADA. The resolution agreement requires the district to revise policies, conduct staff training, and improve documentation practices.</p>
        <div class="entry-sublabel">TLF Interpretation</div>
        <div class="entry-tlf-note">This resolution agreement reinforces OCR's continued prioritization of Section 504 and Title II compliance, particularly regarding timely evaluation, service delivery, and adherence to procedural requirements. Districts must ensure their Section 504 policies, evaluation timelines, and service delivery documentation meet regulatory standards. Staff training on procedural safeguard requirements is now a documented OCR expectation, not a recommended practice.</div>
        <div class="entry-action">
          <div class="entry-action-label">Your Action</div>
          <ul>
            <li>Audit your Section 504 evaluation timelines. Confirm that every student referred for a 504 evaluation received one within your district's documented timeline and that timelines are in writing.</li>
            <li>Review service delivery logs for current 504 students. Confirm services are being provided as written in each plan and that documentation exists to prove it.</li>
            <li>Verify that parent notice and procedural safeguard documentation is on file for every active 504 student. Missing notices are a standalone finding.</li>
            <li>Schedule or confirm staff training on Section 504 procedural requirements. Document the date, participants, and content. This is now an OCR audit expectation.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="entry-source"><strong>Source:</strong> <a href="https://www.ed.gov/media/document/08251823-bpdf" target="_blank">OCR Resolution Agreement, February 2026 ↗</a> · Section 504 of the Rehabilitation Act (29 U.S.C. §794) · Title II of the ADA · 34 CFR Part 104</div>
      </div>
    </div>
 
    <div class="cal-entry ocr" data-program="ocr">
      <div class="entry-inner">
        <div class="entry-top">
          <div class="entry-badge">OCR</div>
          <div class="entry-type-badge">Enforcement Pattern</div>
          <div class="entry-title-block">
            <div class="entry-title">ED Shifts to Rapid Directed Investigations with Shortened Timelines and Funding Threats</div>
            <div class="entry-date">Office for Civil Rights · February through March 2026</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="entry-sublabel">What it says</div>
        <p class="entry-body">Since inauguration, OCR has launched at least seven directed investigations into K-12 districts as of April 3, 2026, primarily focused on LGBTQ+ and transgender policy issues, with significantly accelerated timelines. The Maine case exemplifies the new approach: a 10-day deadline to sign resolution agreements versus the standard 90 days, and referral to DOJ with federal funding on the line.</p>
        <div class="entry-sublabel">TLF Interpretation</div>
        <div class="entry-tlf-note">This is a documented shift in OCR enforcement strategy: expedited directed investigations, compressed response timelines, and immediate DOJ referral with funding consequences for noncompliance. Districts subject to OCR inquiry now have materially less time to respond and negotiate. This enforcement pattern applies primarily to LGBTQ+ and Title IX policies in the current administration's enforcement posture, but the compressed timeline precedent is broader. Every district should be prepared to respond to an OCR inquiry within days, not months.</div>
        <div class="entry-action">
          <div class="entry-action-label">Your Action</div>
          <ul>
            <li>Establish a rapid-response protocol for OCR inquiries now, before one arrives. Identify who is notified, who responds, and who retains legal counsel within 24 hours of an OCR contact.</li>
            <li>Pre-audit your nondiscrimination policies, grievance procedures, and Title IX coordinator documentation. These are the first documents OCR requests. They should be current, board-approved, and retrievable immediately.</li>
            <li>Review your Title IX coordinator designation. Confirm the coordinator is current, trained, and that their contact information is publicly posted as required.</li>
            <li>Brief district legal counsel on the 10-day resolution timeline precedent. Standard 90-day negotiation assumptions no longer apply under the current enforcement posture.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="entry-source"><strong>Source:</strong> <a href="https://www.k12dive.com/news/education-department-OCR-civil-rights-enforcement-DOJ-rapid-investigations-directed/744777/" target="_blank">K-12 Dive analysis, February-March 2026 ↗</a> · OCR directed investigation pattern documentation · Title IX (20 U.S.C. §1681) · Title VI · Section 504</div>
      </div>
    </div>
 
    <div class="cal-entry ocr" data-program="ocr">
      <div class="entry-inner">
        <div class="entry-top">
          <div class="entry-badge">OCR</div>
          <div class="entry-type-badge">Press Release / Policy</div>
          <div class="entry-title-block">
            <div class="entry-title">Department of Education Announces Interagency Agreements Transferring Program Administration to State and HHS</div>
            <div class="entry-date">U.S. Department of Education · February 23, 2026</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="entry-sublabel">What it says</div>
        <p class="entry-body">ED announced two new interagency agreements with the Departments of State and Health and Human Services to transfer administration of select ED programs as part of efforts to reduce the federal education bureaucracy and return education to the states. This includes transferring Section 117 foreign gift reporting oversight to the Department of State.</p>
        <div class="entry-sublabel">TLF Interpretation</div>
        <div class="entry-tlf-note">The initial transfers target higher education and foreign entity oversight, not K-12 formula programs. However, this announcement signals a broader federal strategy to decentralize program administration that could affect future K-12 program oversight, reporting systems, and compliance timelines. Districts should monitor subsequent announcements from ED and their state education agencies regarding whether any K-12 programs will be subject to similar transfers that could alter where reports are filed, who monitors compliance, or how grant funds are administered.</div>
        <div class="entry-action">
          <div class="entry-action-label">Your Action</div>
          <ul>
            <li>No immediate K-12 action required. Current K-12 reporting channels and oversight structures are not affected by this announcement.</li>
            <li>Assign someone on your federal programs team to monitor ED press releases and your state education agency communications for any follow-on announcements affecting K-12 formula or discretionary grants.</li>
            <li>If your district has any postsecondary partnerships or foreign gift reporting obligations under Section 117, consult with legal counsel on how the transfer to the Department of State affects your compliance process.</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="entry-source"><strong>Source:</strong> <a href="https://www.ed.gov/about/news/press-release/us-department-of-education-announces-additional-partnerships-break-federal-education-bureaucracy" target="_blank">U.S. Department of Education press release, February 23, 2026 ↗</a> · Interagency agreements with Departments of State and HHS</div>
      </div>
    </div>
 
    <!-- PERKINS -->
    <div class="cal-section-label" data-section="perkins">Perkins</div>
 
    <div class="cal-entry perkins" data-program="perkins">
      <div class="entry-inner">
        <div class="entry-top">
          <div class="entry-badge">Perkins</div>
          <div class="entry-type-badge">Guidance Document</div>
          <div class="entry-title-block">
            <div class="entry-title">Requirements and Instructions for Perkins V State Plan Revisions and Budgets for FY 2026</div>
            <div class="entry-date">Office of Career, Technical, and Adult Education · February 4, 2026</div>
          </div>
        </div>
        <div class="entry-sublabel">What it says</div>
        <p class="entry-body">The Department published requirements and instructions for state educational agencies to submit Perkins V State Plan revisions and budgets for Fiscal Year 2026 grant awards. This guidance provides technical assistance for states administering career and technical education programs.</p>
        <div class="entry-sublabel">TLF Interpretation</div>
        <div class="entry-tlf-note">This guidance governs state-level Perkins V plan revisions and FY 2026 budget submissions. Local recipients of Perkins funds should monitor their state plan for any revisions that affect local allocation formulas, allowable uses, or reporting requirements. If your state submits plan revisions, local CTE directors should request a summary of changes from the state agency before the next budget cycle to ensure local expenditures remain aligned with the updated plan.</div>
        <div class="entry-action">
          <div class="entry-action-label">Your Action</div>
          <ul>
            <li>Contact your state CTE office to confirm whether a Perkins V State Plan revision is being submitted for FY 2026 and request a summary of any changes affecting local recipients.</li>
            <li>Review your current Perkins budget for alignment with your state plan. If a revision is pending, hold final budget commitments until the updated plan is confirmed.</li>
